climbs.name: The Todd Fellows
climbs.fa: Todd Swain, Brad White, and Dick Peterson

content.description: A short, somewhat painful techy pocket climb which is unnecessarily sporty off the last bolt.
content.location: This starts just right of the start of Pope's Penis in the central area of the School House Wall. It's south facing.

content.description: This west facing flakey route has a poor anchor, so do bring additional slings to bolster it. Also, be aware of loose boulders at top- doesn't this sound inviting?
content.protection: Five (5) lead bolts to an inadequate anchor.
content.location: This climb is located high up in the center of the wall on the back side of the Pope's Penis. While it has been written to approach this route from the top, this sounded way too convoluted to us. There does exist a new five (5) bolt route on the west face off the trail that we felt was 5.11b, A0 (a crucial hold has broken at the start yielding a great big white scar). It allows one to directly approach Perfect Stranger as a two (2) pitch combination.

content.description: There is much that is "baadd" about this route. Poor rock, poor move structure, lack of a safe anchor, and just about all the bolts spin like lathes.
content.protection: Apparently the first ascentionists couldn't afford the cost of a two (2) bolt anchor and chain, tho they did afford seven (7) lead bolts.
content.location: The 2nd sport route from the left.

climbs.name: A Dog Named Fellatio
climbs.fa: Dave Franks, Matt Hudson, and Jeff Giek (11/88)

content.description: The crux is between bolts 4 and 5. Sustained thin face which is very sequential. Most enjoyable w/ two draws on 4 and a long sling on 5. Might have been 10d at one time, tho it felt more like 11b to us now.
content.location: Right most route on the wall. It even has its own approach trail.

climbs.name: A Cat Named Horacio
climbs.fa: Matt Hudson, Jeff Giek, and Dave Franks (11/88)

content.description: This slightly off vertical route should have been protected for the lowest common denominator- it wasn't. It's quite sporty thru its three (3) lead bolts.
content.protection: The anchor almost guarantees major headaches for pulling (it's made up of alot of old slings around a tree in a corner out left). We found that trending right at the end to the crack climbs (Good Buddy 5.7) bolt anchors worked out much better.
content.location: West facing. This is one of the farthest routes on the right just above the other west facing route "Fellatio".

content.description: This wall is just up the road (east) from the Pond area about a quarter mile. It mostly faces south and doesn't see much traffic.
